  "prompt": "What is the difference between to ride and to drive?",
  "response": "Here's the difference between \"to ride\" and \"to drive\":\n\nTo Ride:\n- Typically used when you are a passenger or sitting on something\n- Used for bicycles, horses, motorcycles, buses, trains, etc.\n- You are not controlling the vehicle/animal\n- Examples: \"I ride my bicycle to work\" or \"She rides the bus to school\"\n\nTo Drive:\n- Used when you are controlling a vehicle\n- Specifically for motorized vehicles like cars, trucks, tractors\n- You are the one operating the vehicle\n- Examples: \"He drives a car\" or \"I drive to work every day\"\n\nSome specific uses:\n- You ride a horse\n- You drive a car\n- You ride a bike or motorcycle\n- You drive a truck\n- You ride a bus or train\n- You ride a skateboard\n\nThe key difference is control: riding means being transported, while driving means you are controlling the transportation.",
